1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,400
How we think about disability shapes how we respond to it.

2
00:00:04,400 --> 00:00:09,600
So let us look at three models that have influenced healthcare and society.

3
00:00:09,600 --> 00:00:12,000
The first is the medical model.

4
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:19,600
This model treats disability as a problem located in the individual — something to be diagnosed, treated, or cured.

5
00:00:19,600 --> 00:00:23,200
For decades, this was the dominant view in healthcare.

6
00:00:23,200 --> 00:00:27,200
Under this model, the focus is on fixing the person.

7
00:00:27,200 --> 00:00:29,600
The second is the social model.

8
00:00:29,600 --> 00:00:34,000
This model shifts the focus from the person to the environment.

9
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:45,600
It says that people are disabled not by their bodies or minds, but by barriers in society — stairs instead of ramps, information only in print, attitudes that exclude.

10
00:00:45,600 --> 00:00:49,600
Under this model, the focus is on fixing the barriers.

11
00:00:49,600 --> 00:00:56,000
The third — and the one that guides this series — is the human rights model.

12
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:00,000
This model builds on the social model but goes further.

13
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:06,799
It says that people with disabilities have the right to full participation in every aspect of life.

14
00:01:06,799 --> 00:01:09,599
It is not enough to remove barriers.

15
00:01:09,599 --> 00:01:12,799
We must actively ensure inclusion, dignity, and equity.

16
00:01:12,799 --> 00:01:17,200
At UHN, we use the human rights model as our foundation.

17
00:01:17,200 --> 00:01:21,200
This means we do not just accommodate — we include.
